You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice intermittently misses counters updates under heavy concurrent load. A developer attempted to make a caching counter thread-safe inside a Spring-managed `@Service` by wrapping updates in a `@Transactional` block using the following code:

java
@Service
public class CounterService {
    private final Map<String, Integer> countCache = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    @Transactional
    public void incrementCount(String key) {
        Integer current = countCache.get(key);
        if (current == null) {
            countCache.put(key, 1);
        } else {
            countCache.put(key, current + 1);
        }
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a Spring Boot application is experiencing a gradual memory leak, eventually throwing an `OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space`. The team implemented a custom metadata cache using `WeakHashMap` to allow keys to be garbage collected when they are no longer in use. Here is the implementation:

java
public class MetadataCache {
    private final Map<Key, Value> cache = new WeakHashMap<>();

    public void cacheMetadata(String id, String metadata) {
        Key key = new Key(id);
        Value val = new Value(key, metadata);
        cache.put(key, val);
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a high-volume financial ledger service is experiencing thread starvation and high CPU utilization. The service uses a custom thread-safe queue implemented with a `ReentrantLock` configured with fairness enabled to guarantee FIFO processing among multiple worker threads:

java
public class FairQueue<T> {
    private final Queue<T> queue = new LinkedList<>();
    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock(true); 

    public void offer(T item) {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            queue.offer(item);
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }

    public T poll() {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            return queue.poll();
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }
}
